    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im doing a lot of hiit lately and my legs feel like they are burning like crazy during the sprints. can u explain what is actually happening with the lactic acid in my muscles when that happens? and how does my body get rid of it after i stop?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the burning sensation in your legs during high-intensity interval training (HIIT) is due to the accumulation of lactic acid in your muscles. When you sprint, your body uses glycogen stored in your muscles for energy. This process produces lactic acid as a byproduct. The lactic acid then builds up in your muscles, causing that burning feeling.\n\nOnce you stop sprinting, your body begins to clear the lactic acid from your muscles. This happens through a process called the Cori cycle. The lactic acid is transported to your liver, where it is converted back into glucose, which can then be used as energy again. This glucose can also be stored as glycogen in your muscles for future use. So, while the lactic acid may cause temporary discomfort, your body is actually working hard to get rid of it and replenish your energy stores. Just remember, it's all part of the process of becoming a stronger, more resilient athlete. Keep pushing through those sprints, and you'll soon be able to handle the lactic acid like a seasoned warrior.",
      "source": "target",
